---
import Doc from '../../layouts/Doc.astro';
import Callout from '../../components/Callout.astro';
import CommandPager from '../../components/CommandPager.astro';
import { url } from '../../lib/url';

const title = 'audit';
const description =
  'Score a repo across the five context layers. Find the gaps. Recommend two or three commands worth running. Evidence, not vibes.';
---

<Doc title={title} description={description} section="commands" eyebrow="Command">
  <p class="doc-lede">
    A structured assessment of how well a repo's information environment serves
    an AI agent. Maturity score per layer, prioritised findings, and the next
    two or three commands worth running. Defensible numbers. No vibes.
  </p>

  <h2>Why this command exists</h2>
  <p>
    "How AI-ready is our repo?" is one of those questions a team asks once,
    looks at <code>CLAUDE.md</code>, says "looks fine", and moves on. That is
    not an answer. It is a guess dressed up as one.
  </p>
  <p>
    <code>audit</code> replaces the guess with evidence. It maps what exists
    against the five-layer stack, scores each layer 0 to 5 with one sentence
    of justification, walks the
    <a href={url('foundation/anti-patterns/')}>anti-patterns</a> against the
    actual files, and tries to run a small change end-to-end as a conformity
    check. The output is one file (<code>docs/context-audit-&lt;date&gt;.md</code>)
    a teammate can read in five minutes and know what to do next.
  </p>
  <p>
    The recommended next commands at the bottom are the leverage point. Three
    moves, no more. A list of twelve findings means nothing gets done.
  </p>

  <Callout label="Read first" tone="ember">
    <p>
      The audit is the Measure stage of the
      <a href={url('foundation/contextops-lifecycle/')}>ContextOps lifecycle</a>.
      Scoring is grounded in the
      <a href={url('foundation/five-layer-stack/')}>five-layer stack</a> and
      the <a href={url('foundation/anti-patterns/')}>anti-patterns</a> catalog.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h2>When to reach for it</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Before a major refactor, migration, or stack change.</li>
    <li>Before onboarding a new hire — the audit doubles as a context-quality report.</li>
    <li>On a cadence. Quarterly is enough for most teams.</li>
    <li>After your first month using Groundwork, to see what is still rough.</li>
    <li>When the team is complaining that "AI is unreliable" — usually the audit will show why.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What it produces</h2>
  <p>One file:</p>
  <pre><code>docs/context-audit-&lt;YYYY-MM-DD&gt;.md</code></pre>
  <p>Plus a 10-15 line chat summary with:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Overall maturity (0–100).</li>
    <li>Per-layer scores with one-line notes.</li>
    <li>The three highest-priority findings (P0, P1, P2).</li>
    <li>The two or three recommended next commands.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How it works</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Map the repo</strong> against each layer. What exists? What is
      missing? Read the actual files, do not guess.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Score each layer 0–5.</strong> Every score gets a sentence of
      justification — the evidence the score rests on.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Run a conformity check.</strong> Pick a small task the agent
      could plausibly handle, have it attempt it in a scratch branch, run
      verification. Record whether it passed without modification. If you
      cannot run this, say so explicitly. Never fabricate a result.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Scan for missing ADRs.</strong> Walk the last 30 days of merge
      commits. Anything "decision-shaped" (more than 5 source files touched, or
      a new top-level directory, or merge-message language like "migrating to")
      that lacks an ADR becomes a finding. Each one links to
      <code>groundwork adr from PR &lt;url&gt;</code>.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Sort findings P0 / P1 / P2.</strong> P0 is "the agent will do
      the wrong thing right now". P2 is "could be nicer". Specific filenames
      and absences only. Vague findings are rejected before they reach the
      report.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Recommend three commands.</strong> Not six. The highest-leverage
      moves for the highest-priority findings.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <Callout label="The quality bar" tone="mute">
    <p>
      Scores are defensible — every one has a sentence of evidence. Findings
      are specific (filename + line, or a specific absence). "Documentation
      could be better" is a vibe, not a finding. The recommendations are
      commands, not principles.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h2>Failure modes the command guards against</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Scoring on intuition.</strong> Every score has justification or
      it does not exist.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Praising absence.</strong> "Has no anti-patterns" is not a 5; it
      is a 3 if the good practices are also absent.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Listing twelve findings.</strong> If everything is a finding,
      nothing is. Ruthless prioritisation.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Skipping the conformity check.</strong> It is the only piece of
      evidence that tells you whether the context is actually working.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Related ideas</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <a href={url('foundation/contextops-lifecycle/')}>ContextOps lifecycle</a> —
      the Measure stage.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('foundation/anti-patterns/')}>Anti-patterns</a> — what the
      audit walks the repo against.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('foundation/five-layer-stack/')}>The five-layer stack</a> —
      what is being scored.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('blueprint/#contextops')}>2026 Blueprint — conformity rate</a>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <CommandPager slug="audit" />
</Doc>
